1st year bird in crisp juvenal plumage.   Found at about 9:45 am, as seen from the wood pedestrian bridge.  On the island with approximately 1,000 Elegant Terns - but more associated with a few Least Sandpipers and staying away from the terns.  Medium-sized shorebird, larger than pectoral, small than knot.   Had a very dumpy posture, not uncommon for juveniles, almost like a Green Heron when its head is down.   Bold, plain dark scapular feathers - which is the first thing I notice with Ruffs, with wide buffy fringes, all feathers appearing even aged.  Head and neck were dull buff color, no streaking on breast or belly.  Thin dark slightly-decurved "Dunlin-type" bill.  Dull green-yellow  "Willet-like" legs.  Head appears small for body, giving a hunched appearance when feeding.  Floppy rear wing feathers (extended tertials?) also diagnostic.

I showed up at 7AM, but the gate is locked until 9.  From the entrance kiosk at 7 I was able to see several grouse in the green field, about 12 flew up to the right to a relatively bald spot on the hill slope, which is about 500 feet to the right of the entrance kiosk.  A photo that I took of the hillside show about 45 Grouse roosting there.  At 9AM was able to enter the park normally.  Found 8 of them in the town (adults and juveniles), varying between the sage and the green grass.   Using the abandoned buildings as a blind seems effective for getting close up shots.  The roosting spot was empty at 9:30AM, they are spread out around the park.

Seen from 8:50 to 9:10 PM on the main trail at about 1.25 miles from gate, after the first large trail junction.  Dark, no moon.   There were two pair of poorwill sitting in trail or along vegetative edges.  Saw eye shine first.  The attached photo of the male was taken at the main junction in dark with a small flashlight.  Strong white wing tips in flight showing.

Pale bird, slaty gray and white, likely indicating P. nuttallii nuttalli, nominate interior race and not Dusky Poorwill ssp. californicus.   These are believed to migrate from Eastern Oregon/Washington and Great Basin down the coast in early october into Northern Mexico.   Bird was resting on footpath out in the open, with eye occasionally partly open in the NE corner of the community garden, easily seen from outside the fence.   Found by David Assmann about an hour earlier.
On nest, nesting in cliff too close, about 10.5' from the metal railing.  I'm concerned about excessive nest disturbance.  Photos later.

photos.Locality: McNear Brickyard (Private Property/Authorization for Access Required)
photos.Observation Details: 4000 per Rusty Scalf.     Started photographing at 6:17 PM, conditions very windy, dry northerly wind, lots of sea chop.  Fewer than a dozen swifts for the first 25 minutes.   At 6:40 PM they started pouring out of the chimney by the thousands when buzzed by a Peregrine, who harassed them for about five minutes before leaving.   We figured they had gone in early (before 6PM) because of high winds.  2500-4000 remained circling for 30 minutes before re-entering.  Photos.

Found the nesting spot in a deep ravine and was treated to many (hundred's?) in flight around the box canyon.  Poor light for photography.  The colony was built into the side of the cliff.  Evidently one of three known breeding sites on island.  Split now recognized by IOC and Birdlife as Tahiti Swiftlet.
